    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-08-16T06:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-08-16T06:30:00-05:00" n="344"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d344">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">788.00/8–1653: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 344<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iran (<persName corresp="#p_MGH1" type="from"
                            >Mattison</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d344fn1">Repeated to London and Beirut for Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_HLW1">Henderson</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-08-16T15:00:00+03:30"
                            >August 16, 1953—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>342. Late morning August 16, correspondents <persName>Donald Schwind</persName>,
                    Associated Press, and <persName>Kenneth Love</persName>, <hi rend="italic">New
                        York Times</hi>, went to hills north of Tehran at request son of <persName
                        corresp="#p_ZMF1">General Zahedi</persName> for conference. <persName
                        corresp="#p_ZMF1">Zahedi</persName> not present, but son showed signed
                    decree from Shah and gave photostats of it to newsmen.</p>
                <p>Decree, signed by Shah, dated Thursday, August 13, 1953, said: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“View of fact situation of nation necessitates appointment of an informed
                            and experienced man who can grasp affairs of country readily, I
                            therefore, with knowledge I have of your ability and <pb facs="0772"
                                n="746" xml:id="pg_746"/> merit, appoint you with this letter Prime
                            Minister. We give into your hands duty to improve affairs of the nation
                            and remove present crisis and raise living standard of people.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_ZMF1">Zahedi</persName>’s son said father naturally in
                    hiding; that coup not intended; that Colonel <persName>Nasari</persName> went to
                    Prime Minister’s home this morning with soldiers to present this decree to
                        <persName corresp="#p_MM1">Mosadeq</persName> and was arrested by
                    guards.</p>
                <p>Translator US Embassy, well acquainted with Shah’s signature because previous
                    employment, saw photostat and declared belief Shah’s signature genuine.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MGH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mattison</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
